<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12017&amp;p=136392#p136392</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12017&amp;p=136392#p136392"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Open Source / Distributable Games?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12017&amp;p=136392#p136392"><![CDATA[
With virtual gamepads as you have depicted, how can the player tell where his thumbs are relative to the on-screen controls? I have found that the problem isn't just &quot;enough space between&quot;; it's also a problem of &quot;whiffing&quot;, or accidentally pressing outside the boundaries of <em>any</em> valid button because my thumbs have drifted from their intended positions. I tried playing <a href="https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=dk.progressivemedia.pixelinejungleskattenosaoFREE&amp;hl=en" class="postlink">the free subset of <em>Pixeline and the Jungle Treasure</em></a> on my Nexus 7 tablet, and my thumbs kept drifting from the on-screen controls. I had the same problem with Nesoid, an NES emulator, on the same tablet. The number of controls you can reliably press with each thumb without looking is <em>one.</em> This is why so many games for touch-screen devices, such as <em>Canabalt</em> and <em>Rayman Jungle Run</em>, are endless runners.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Thu Nov 13, 2014 2:47 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
